# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: motion-blur-rendering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] In photography, **exposure** is the amount of light per unit area reaching a frame of photographic film or the surface of an electronic image sensor.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] It is determined by exposure time, lens f-number, and scene luminance.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Exposure is measured in units of lux-seconds (symbol lx⋅s), and can be computed from exposure value (EV) and scene luminance in a specified region.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] An "exposure" is a single shutter cycle.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] For example, a long exposure refers to a single, long shutter cycle to gather enough dim light, whereas a multiple exposure involves a series of shutter cycles, effectively layering a series of photographs in one image.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] The accumulated *photometric exposure* (*H*v) is the same so long as the total exposure time is the same.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Only in this appropriately weighted case does the H measure the effective amount of light falling on the film, such that the characteristic curve will be correct independent of the spectrum of the light.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Many photographic materials are also sensitive to "invisible" light, which can be a nuisance , or a benefit .
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] The use of radiometric units is appropriate to characterize such sensitivity to invisible light.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] In sensitometric data, such as characteristic curves, the *log exposure* is conventionally expressed as log10(*H*).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Photographers more familiar with base-2 logarithmic scales (such as exposure values) can convert using log2(*H*) ≈ 3.32 log10(*H*).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] So-called "correct" exposure may be defined as an exposure that achieves the effect the photographer intended.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] A more technical approach recognises that a photographic film (or sensor) has a physically limited useful exposure range, sometimes called its dynamic range.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] If, for any part of the photograph, the actual exposure is outside this range, the film cannot record it accurately.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] In a very simple model, for example, out-of-range values would be recorded as "black" (underexposed) or "white" (overexposed) rather than the precisely graduated shades of colour and tone required to describe "detail".
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Therefore, the purpose of exposure adjustment (and/or lighting adjustment) is to control the physical amount of light from the subject that is allowed to fall on the film, so that 'significant' areas of shadow and highlight detail do not exceed the film's useful exposure range.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] This ensures that no 'significant' information is lost during capture.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] The photographer may carefully overexpose or underexpose the photograph to *eliminate* what they judge as insignificant or unwanted detail; to make, for example, a white altar cloth appear immaculately clean, or to emulate the heavy, pitiless shadows of film noir.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] However, it is technically much easier to discard recorded information during post processing than to try to 're-create' unrecorded information.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] In a scene with strong or harsh lighting, the *ratio* between highlight and shadow luminance values may well be larger than the ratio between the film's maximum and minimum useful exposure values.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] A photograph may be described as *overexposed* when it has a loss of highlight detail, that is, when important bright parts of an image are "washed out" or effectively all white, known as "blown-out highlights" or "clipped whites".
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] A photograph may be described as *underexposed* when it has a loss of shadow detail, that is, when important dark areas are "muddy" or indistinguishable from black, known as "blocked-up shadows" (or sometimes "crushed shadows", "crushed blacks", or "clipped blacks", especially in video).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] As the adjacent image shows, these terms are technical ones rather than artistic judgments; an overexposed or underexposed image may be "correct" in the sense that it provides the effect that the photographer intended.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Intentionally over- or underexposing (relative to a standard or the camera's automatic exposure) is casually referred to as "exposing to the right" or "exposing to the left" respectively, as these shift the histogram of the image to the right or left.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] In manual mode, the photographer adjusts the lens aperture and/or shutter speed to achieve the desired exposure.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Many photographers choose to control aperture and shutter independently because opening up the aperture increases exposure, but also decreases the depth of field, and a slower shutter increases exposure but also increases the opportunity for motion blur.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] "Manual" exposure calculations may be based on some method of light metering with a working knowledge of exposure values, the APEX system and/or the Zone System.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] A camera in **automatic exposure** or **autoexposure** (usually initialized as **AE**) mode automatically calculates and adjusts exposure settings to match (as closely as possible) the subject's mid-tone to the mid-tone of the photograph.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] For most cameras, this means using an on-board TTL exposure meter.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Aperture priority (commonly abbreviated as *A*, or *Av* for "aperture value") mode gives the photographer manual control of the aperture, whilst the camera automatically adjusts the shutter speed to achieve the exposure specified by the TTL meter.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Shutter priority (often abbreviated as *S*, or *Tv* for "time value") mode gives manual shutter control, with automatic aperture compensation.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] In each case, the actual exposure level is still determined by the camera's exposure meter.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] The purpose of an exposure meter is to estimate the subject's mid-tone luminance and indicate the camera exposure settings required to record this as a mid-tone.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] In order to do this it has to make a number of assumptions which, under certain circumstances, will be wrong.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] If the exposure setting indicated by an exposure meter is taken as the "reference" exposure, the photographer may wish to deliberately *overexpose* or *underexpose* in order to compensate for known or anticipated metering inaccuracies.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Cameras with any kind of internal exposure meter usually feature an exposure compensation setting which is intended to allow the photographer to simply offset the exposure level from the internal meter's estimate of appropriate exposure.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Frequently calibrated in stops, also known as EV units, a "+1" exposure compensation setting indicates one stop more (twice as much) exposure and "−1" means one stop less (half as much) exposure.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Exposure compensation is particularly useful in combination with auto-exposure mode, as it allows the photographer to *bias* the exposure level without resorting to full manual exposure and losing the flexibility of auto exposure.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] On low-end video camcorders, exposure compensation may be the only manual exposure control available.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] An appropriate exposure for a photograph is determined by the sensitivity of the medium used.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] For photographic film, sensitivity is referred to as film speed and is measured on a scale published by the International Organization for Standardization (ISO).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Faster film, that is, film with a higher ISO rating, requires less exposure to make a readable image.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Digital cameras usually have variable ISO settings that provide additional flexibility.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Exposure is a combination of the length of time and the illuminance at the photosensitive material.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Exposure time is controlled in a camera by shutter speed, and the illuminance depends on the lens aperture and the scene luminance.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Slower shutter speeds (exposing the medium for a longer period of time), greater lens apertures (admitting more light), and higher-luminance scenes produce greater exposures.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] An approximately correct exposure will be obtained on a sunny day using ISO 100 film, an aperture of f/16 and a shutter speed of 1⁄100 of a second.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] This is called the sunny 16 rule: at an aperture of f/16 on a sunny day, a suitable shutter speed will be one over the film speed (or closest equivalent).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] A scene can be exposed in many ways, depending on the desired effect a photographer wishes to convey.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] An important principle of exposure is reciprocity.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] If one exposes the film or sensor for a longer period, a reciprocally smaller aperture is required to reduce the amount of light hitting the film to obtain the same exposure.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] For example, the photographer may prefer to make their sunny-16 shot at an aperture of f/5.6 (to obtain a shallow depth of field).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] As f/5.6 is 3 **stops** "faster" than f/16, with each stop meaning double the amount of light, a new shutter speed of (1⁄125)/(2·2·2) = 1⁄1000 s is needed.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Once the photographer has determined the exposure, aperture stops can be traded for halvings or doublings of speed, within limits.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] The true characteristic of most photographic emulsions is not actually linear (see sensitometry), but it is close enough over the exposure range of about 1 second to 1⁄1000 of a second.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Outside of this range, it becomes necessary to increase the exposure from the calculated value to account for this characteristic of the emulsion.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] This characteristic is known as *reciprocity failure*.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] The film manufacturer's data sheets should be consulted to arrive at the correction required, as different emulsions have different characteristics.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Digital camera image sensors can also be subject to a form of reciprocity failure.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] The Zone System is another method of determining exposure and development combinations to achieve a greater tonality range over conventional methods by varying the contrast of the film to fit the print contrast capability.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Digital cameras can achieve similar results (high dynamic range) by combining several different exposures (varying shutter or diaphragm) made in quick succession.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Today, most cameras automatically determine the correct exposure at the time of taking a photograph by using a built-in light meter, or multiple point meters interpreted by a built-in computer, see metering mode.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Negative and print film tends to bias for exposing for the shadow areas (film dislikes being starved of light), with digital favouring exposure for highlights.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Latitude is the degree by which one can over, or under expose an image, and still recover an acceptable level of quality from an exposure.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Typically negative film has a better ability to record a range of brightness than slide/transparency film or digital.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Digital should be considered to be the reverse of print film, with a good latitude in the shadow range, and a narrow one in the highlight area; in contrast to film's large highlight latitude, and narrow shadow latitude.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Slide/Transparency film has a narrow latitude in both highlight and shadow areas, requiring greater exposure accuracy.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Negative film's latitude increases somewhat with high ISO material, in contrast digital tends to narrow on latitude with high ISO settings.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Areas of a photo where information is lost due to extreme brightness are described as having "blown-out highlights" or "flared highlights".
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] In digital images this information loss is often irreversible, though small problems can be made less noticeable using photo manipulation software.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Recording to raw image format can correct this problem to some degree, as can using a digital camera with a better sensor.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Film can often have areas of extreme overexposure but still record detail in those areas.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] This information is usually somewhat recoverable when printing or transferring to digital.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] A loss of highlights in a photograph is usually undesirable, but in some cases can be considered to "enhance" appeal.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Examples include black and white photography and portraits with an out-of-focus background.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Areas of a photo where information is lost due to extreme darkness are described as "crushed blacks".
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Digital capture tends to be more tolerant of underexposure, allowing better recovery of shadow detail, than same-ISO negative print film.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/exposure-photography] Crushed blacks cause loss of detail, but can be used for artistic effect.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] In image processing, a **Gaussian blur** (also known as **Gaussian smoothing**) is the result of blurring an image by a Gaussian function (named after mathematician and scientist Carl Friedrich Gauss).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] It is a widely used effect in graphics software, typically to reduce image noise and reduce definition.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] The visual effect of this blurring technique is a smooth blur resembling that of viewing the image through a translucent screen, distinctly different from the bokeh effect produced by an out-of-focus lens or the shadow of an object under usual illumination.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Gaussian smoothing is also used as a pre-processing stage in computer vision algorithms in order to enhance image structures at different scales—see scale space representation and scale space implementation.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Mathematically, applying a Gaussian blur to an image is the same as convolving the image with a Gaussian function.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] This is also known as a two-dimensional Weierstrass transform.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] By contrast, convolving by a circle (i.e., a circular box blur) would more accurately reproduce the bokeh effect.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Since the Fourier transform of a Gaussian is another Gaussian, applying a Gaussian blur has the effect of reducing the image's high-frequency components; a Gaussian blur is thus a low-pass filter.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] The Gaussian blur is a type of image-blurring filter that uses a Gaussian function (which also expresses the normal distribution in statistics) for calculating the transformation to apply to each pixel in the image.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] The origin on these axes are at the center (0, 0).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] When applied in two dimensions, this formula produces a surface whose contours are concentric circles with a Gaussian distribution from the center point.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Values from this distribution are used to build a convolution matrix which is applied to the original image.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] This convolution process is illustrated visually in the figure on the right.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Each pixel's new value is set to a weighted average of that pixel's neighborhood.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] The original pixel's value receives the heaviest weight (having the highest Gaussian value) and neighboring pixels receive smaller weights as their distance to the original pixel increases.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] This results in a blur that preserves boundaries and edges better than other, more uniform blurring filters; see also scale space implementation.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] In theory, the Gaussian function at every point on the image will be non-zero, meaning that the entire image would need to be included in the calculations for each pixel.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] In practice, when computing a discrete approximation of the Gaussian function, pixels at a distance of more than 3*σ* have a small enough influence to be considered effectively zero.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Thus contributions from pixels outside that range can be ignored.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Typically, an image processing program need only calculate a matrix with dimensions $\lceil 6\sigma \rceil$ × $\lceil 6\sigma \rceil$ (where $\lceil \cdot \rceil$ is the ceiling function) to ensure a result sufficiently close to that obtained by the entire Gaussian distribution.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] In addition to being circularly symmetric, the Gaussian blur can be applied to a two-dimensional image as two independent one-dimensional calculations, and so is termed a separable filter.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] That is, the effect of applying the two-dimensional matrix can also be achieved by applying a series of single-dimensional Gaussian matrices in the horizontal direction, then repeating the process in the vertical direction.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Applying successive Gaussian blurs to an image has the same effect as applying a single, larger Gaussian blur, whose radius is the square root of the sum of the squares of the blur radii that were actually applied.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] For example, applying successive Gaussian blurs with radii of 6 and 8 gives the same results as applying a single Gaussian blur of radius 10, since ${\sqrt {6^{2}+8^{2}}}=10$ .
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Because of this relationship, processing time cannot be saved by simulating a Gaussian blur with successive, smaller blurs — the time required will be at least as great as performing the single large blur.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Gaussian blurring is commonly used when reducing the size of an image.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] When downsampling an image, it is common to apply a low-pass filter to the image prior to resampling.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] This is to ensure that spurious high-frequency information does not appear in the downsampled image (aliasing).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Gaussian blurs have nice properties, such as having no sharp edges, and thus do not introduce ringing into the filtered image.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Gaussian blur is a low-pass filter, attenuating high frequency signals.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Its amplitude Bode plot (the log scale in the frequency domain) is a parabola.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] This sample matrix is produced by sampling the Gaussian filter kernel (with σ = 0.84089642) at the midpoints of each pixel and then normalizing.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] The center element (at [0, 0]) has the largest value, decreasing symmetrically as distance from the center increases.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Since the filter kernel's origin is at the center, the matrix starts at ${\textstyle G(-R,-R)}$ and ends at ${\textstyle G(R,R)}$ where R equals the kernel radius.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] The element 0.22508352 (the central one) is 1177 times larger than 0.00019117 which is just outside 3σ.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] A Gaussian blur effect is typically generated by convolving an image with an FIR kernel of Gaussian values.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] In practice, it is best to take advantage of the Gaussian blur’s separable property by dividing the process into two passes.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] In the first pass, a one-dimensional kernel is used to blur the image in only the horizontal or vertical direction.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] In the second pass, the same one-dimensional kernel is used to blur in the remaining direction.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Discretization is typically achieved by sampling the Gaussian filter kernel at discrete points, normally at positions corresponding to the midpoints of each pixel.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] This reduces the computational cost but, for very small filter kernels, point sampling the Gaussian function with very few samples leads to a large error.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] In these cases, accuracy is maintained (at a slight computational cost) by integration of the Gaussian function over each pixel's area.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] When converting the Gaussian’s continuous values into the discrete values needed for a kernel, the sum of the values will be different from 1.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] This will cause a darkening or brightening of the image.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] To remedy this, the values can be normalized by dividing each term in the kernel by the sum of all terms in the kernel.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] For a more detailed description about the discrete analogue of the Gaussian kernel, see the article on scale-space implementation and.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] The efficiency of FIR breaks down for high sigmas.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] These include the very fast multiple box blurs, the fast and accurate IIR Deriche edge detector, a "stack blur" based on the box blur, and more.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] For processing pre-recorded temporal signals or video, the Gaussian kernel can also be used for smoothing over the temporal domain, since the data are pre-recorded and available in all directions.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] When processing temporal signals or video in real-time situations, the Gaussian kernel cannot, however, be used for temporal smoothing, since it would access data from the future, which obviously cannot be available.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] The time-causal limit kernel corresponds to convolution with an infinite number of truncated exponential kernels coupled in cascade, with specifically chosen time constants.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] For discrete data, this kernel can often be numerically well approximated by a small set of first-order recursive filters coupled in cascade, see for further details.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Gaussian smoothing is commonly used with edge detection.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Most edge-detection algorithms are sensitive to noise; the 2-D Laplacian filter, built from a discretization of the Laplace operator, is highly sensitive to noisy environments.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Using a Gaussian Blur filter before edge detection aims to reduce the level of noise in the image, which improves the result of the following edge-detection algorithm.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] This approach is commonly referred to as Laplacian of Gaussian, or LoG filtering.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Lower-end digital cameras, including many mobile phone cameras, commonly use gaussian blurring to obscure image noise caused by higher ISO light sensitivities.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/gaussian-blur] Gaussian blur is automatically applied as part of the image post-processing of the photo by the camera software, leading to an irreversible loss of detail.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] When a camera creates an image, that image does not represent a single instant of time.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Because of technological constraints or artistic requirements, the image may represent the scene over a period of time.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Most often this exposure time is brief enough that the image captured by the camera appears to capture an instantaneous moment, but this is not always so, and a fast moving object or a longer exposure time may result in blurring artifacts which make this apparent.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] As objects in a scene move, an image of that scene must represent an integration of all positions of those objects, as well as the camera's viewpoint, over the period of exposure determined by the shutter speed.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] In such an image, any object moving with respect to the camera will look blurred or smeared along the direction of relative motion.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] This smearing may occur on an object that is moving or on a static background if the camera is moving.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] In a film or television image, this looks natural because the human eye behaves in much the same way.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Because the effect is caused by the relative motion between the camera, and the objects and scene, motion blur may be manipulated by panning the camera to track those moving objects.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] In this case, even with long exposure times, the moving objects will appear sharper while the background will become more blurred, with the resulting image conveying a sense of movement and speed.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] In computer animation this effect must be simulated as a virtual camera actually does capture a discrete moment in time.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] This simulated motion blur is typically applied when either the camera or objects in the scene move rapidly.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Without this simulated effect each frame shows a perfect instant in time (analogous to a camera with an infinitely fast shutter), with zero motion blur.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] This is why a video game with a frame rate of 25–30 frames per second will seem staggered, while natural motion filmed at the same frame rate appears rather more continuous.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Many modern video games feature motion blur, especially vehicle simulation games.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Some of the better-known games that utilise this are the recent Need for Speed titles, Unreal Tournament III, The Legend of Zelda: Majora's Mask, among many others.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Classic "motion blur" effects prior to modern per-pixel shading pipelines often simply drew successive frames on top of each other with slight transparency, which is strictly speaking a form of video feedback.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] In pre-rendered computer animation, such as CGI movies, realistic motion blur can be drawn because the renderer has more time to draw each frame.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Temporal anti-aliasing produces frames as a composite of many instants.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Frames are not points in time, they are periods of time.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] If an object makes a trip at a linear speed along a path from 0% to 100% in four time periods, and if those time periods are considered frames, then the object would exhibit motion blur streaks in each frame that are 25% of the path length.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] If the shutter speed is shortened to less than the duration of a frame, and it may be so shortened as to approach zero time in duration, then the computer animator must choose which portion of the quarter paths (in our 4 frame example) they wish to feature as "open shutter" times.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] They may choose to render the beginnings of each frame, in which case they will never see the arrival of the object at the end of the path, or they may choose to render the ends of each frame, in which case they will miss the starting point of the trip.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Most computer animation systems make the classic "fence-post error" in the way they handle time, confusing the periods of time of an animation with the instantaneous moments that delimit them.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Motion lines in cel animation are drawn in the same direction as motion blur and perform much the same duty.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Go motion is a variant of stop motion animation that moves the models during the exposure to create a less staggered effect.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] In 2D computer graphics, motion blur is an artistic filter that converts the digital image/bitmap/raster image in order to simulate the effect.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Adobe Photoshop or GIMP) offer simple motion blur filters.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] However, for advanced motion blur filtering including curves or non-uniform speed adjustment, specialized software products (e.g.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] When an animal's eye is in motion, the image will suffer from motion blur, resulting in an inability to resolve details.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] To cope with this, humans generally alternate between saccades (quick eye movements) and fixation (focusing on a single point).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Saccadic masking makes motion blur during a saccade invisible.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Similarly, smooth pursuit allows the eye to track a target in rapid motion, eliminating motion blur of that target instead of the scene.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] If their velocity exceeds the temporal resolution of the visual system, moving figures will be rendered with smeared contours or as a streaks that average the received light across its path.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] The effect is more obvious with luminous objects moving through darkness, due to the relative sluggish processing by rod cells that dominate scotopic vision.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] In televised sports, where conventional cameras expose pictures 25 or 30 times per second, motion blur can be inconvenient because it obscures the exact position of a projectile or athlete in slow motion.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] For this reason special cameras are often used which eliminate motion blurring by taking rapid exposures on the order of 1 millisecond, and then transmitting them over the course of the next 30 to 40 milliseconds.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Although this gives sharper slow motion replays, it can look strange at normal speeds because the eye expects to see motion blurring and is not provided with blurred images.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Conversely, extra motion blur can unavoidably occur on displays when it is not desired.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] This occurs with some video displays (especially LCD) that exhibits motion blur during fast motion.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] This can lead to more perceived motion blurring above and beyond the preexisting motion blur in the video material.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Sometimes, motion blur can be removed from images with the help of deconvolution.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] In video games the use or not of motion blur is somewhat controversial.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Some players claim that the blur actually makes the game worse, as it does blur images, making it more difficult to recognize objects (especially so in fast-paced moments).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] This does become more noticeable (and more problematic) with a reduction in framerate.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Improvements in the visual quality of modern post-process motion blur shaders as well as a tendency towards higher framerates have lessened the visual detriment of undersampled motion blur effects.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Birds cannot properly see the swirling blades of wind turbines and can get struck by them fatally.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] A 2020 report from Norway suggests that painting one of the three blades with a black tip makes the blades more visible and hence more avoidable.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] This reduces the motion blur of the unpainted blades, and cuts bird deaths by up to 70 percent.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] During aerial mapping an aircraft or drone is used to take pictures of the ground during flight.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] If the flight speed is too high or if shutter speeds are too long, this can lead to motion blur.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Motion blur reduces the quality of the images and has a negative effect on the mapping products.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Motion blur can be avoided by adjusting the flight altitude, flight velocity, or shutter speed.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] From left: original image, blurred image and de-blurred image.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-blur] Notice some artifacts in the de-blurred image.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] In computer vision and image processing, **motion estimation** is the process of determining *motion vectors* that describe the transformation from one 2D image to another; usually from adjacent frames in a video sequence.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] It is an ill-posed problem as the motion happens in three dimensions (3D) but the images are a projection of the 3D scene onto a 2D plane.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] The motion vectors may relate to the whole image (*global motion estimation*) or specific parts, such as rectangular blocks, arbitrary shaped patches or even per pixel.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] The motion vectors may be represented by a translational model or many other models that can approximate the motion of a real video camera, such as rotation and translation in all three dimensions and zoom.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] More often than not, the term motion estimation and the term *optical flow* are used interchangeably.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] It is also related in concept to *image registration* and *stereo correspondence*.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] In fact all of these terms refer to the process of finding corresponding points between two images or video frames.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] The points that correspond to each other in two views (images or frames) of a real scene or object are "usually" the same point in that scene or on that object.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] Before we do motion estimation, we must define our measurement of correspondence, i.e., the matching metric, which is a measurement of how similar two image points are.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] There is no right or wrong here; the choice of matching metric is usually related to what the final estimated motion is used for as well as the optimisation strategy in the estimation process.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] Each *motion vector* is used to represent a *macroblock* in a picture based on the position of this macroblock (or a similar one) in another picture, called the reference picture.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] The methods for finding motion vectors can be categorised into pixel based methods ("direct") and feature based methods ("indirect").
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] A famous debate resulted in two papers from the opposing factions being produced to try to establish a conclusion.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] Statistical functions that have been successfully used include RANSAC.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] It can be argued that almost all methods require some kind of definition of the matching criteria.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] The difference is only whether you summarise over a local image region first and then compare the summarisation (such as feature based methods), or you compare each pixel first (such as squaring the difference) and then summarise over a local image region (block base motion and filter based motion).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] An emerging type of matching criteria summarises a local image region first for every pixel location (through some feature transform such as Laplacian transform), compares each summarised pixel and summarises over a local image region again.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] Some matching criteria have the ability to exclude points that do not actually correspond to each other albeit producing a good matching score, others do not have this ability, but they are still matching criteria.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] Affine motion estimation is a technique used in computer vision and image processing to estimate the motion between two images or frames.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] It assumes that the motion can be modeled as an affine transformation (translation + rotation + zooming), which is a linear transformation followed by a translation.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] Applying the motion vectors to an image to synthesize the transformation to the next image is called motion compensation.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] It is most easily applied to discrete cosine transform (DCT) based video coding standards, because the coding is performed in blocks.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] As a way of exploiting temporal redundancy, motion estimation and compensation are key parts of video compression.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] Almost all video coding standards use block-based motion estimation and compensation such as the MPEG series including the most recent HEVC.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/motion-vector] In simultaneous localization and mapping, a 3D model of a scene is reconstructed using images from a moving camera.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] The rolling shutter can be either mechanical or electronic.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] The advantage of this electronic rolling shutter is that the image sensor can continue to gather photons during the acquisition process, thus effectively increasing sensitivity.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] It is found on many digital still and video cameras using CMOS sensors.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] The effect is most noticeable when imaging extreme conditions of motion or the fast flashing of light.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] While some CMOS sensors use a global shutter, the majority found in the consumer market use a rolling shutter.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] CCDs (charge-coupled devices) are alternatives to CMOS sensors, which are generally more sensitive and more expensive.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] CCD-based cameras often use global shutters, which take a snapshot representing a “relative” single instant in time and therefore do not suffer from the motion artifacts caused by rolling shutters.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] The effects of a rolling shutter can prove difficult for visual effects filming.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] The process of matchmoving establishes perspective in a scene based on a single point in time, but this is difficult with a rolling shutter that provides multiple points in time within the same frame.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] Final results depend on the readout speed of the sensor and the nature of the scene being filmed; as a rule of thumb, higher-end cinema cameras will have faster readout speeds and therefore milder rolling shutter artifacts than low-end cameras.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] Images and video that suffer from rolling shutter distortion can be improved by algorithms that do rolling shutter *rectification*, or rolling shutter *compensation*.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] How to do this is an active area of research.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] This effect can be used as a side channel attack to gain secret keys from certain smart card readers: The attacker films the power LED of the reader while the reader is performing a cryptographic operation, then analyzes the video footage to identify brief voltage fluctuations.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] Due to the effect of the rolling shutter, the footage will reveal fluctuations at a resolution several orders of magnitude greater than the frame rate of the video camera.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] With knowledge about the algorithm used and its implementation in the chip, the attacker can then derive the key.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/rolling-shutter] Analyzing video footage is equivalent to measuring power consumption with an oscilloscope, but less invasive.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] In photography, **shutter speed** or **exposure time** is the length of time that the film or digital sensor inside the camera is exposed to light (that is, when the camera's shutter is open) when taking a photograph.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] The amount of light that reaches the film or image sensor is proportional to the exposure time.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] 1⁄500 of a second will let half as much light in as 1⁄250.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] The camera's shutter speed, the lens's aperture or f-stop, and the scene's luminance together determine the amount of light that reaches the film or sensor (the exposure).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Exposure value (EV) is a quantity that accounts for the shutter speed and the f-number.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Once the sensitivity to light of the recording surface (either film or sensor) is set in numbers expressed in "ISOs" (e.g.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] 200 ISO, 400 ISO), the light emitted by the scene photographed can be controlled through aperture and shutter-speed to match the film or sensor sensitivity to light.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] This will achieve a good exposure when all the details of the scene are legible on the photograph.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Too much light let into the camera results in an overly pale image (or "over-exposure") while too little light will result in an overly dark image (or "under-exposure").
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Multiple combinations of shutter speed and f-number can give the same exposure value (E.V.).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] According to exposure value formula, doubling the exposure time doubles the amount of light (subtracts 1 EV).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Reducing the aperture size at multiples of one over the square root of two lets half as much light into the camera, usually at a predefined scale of f/1, f/1.4, f/2, f/2.8, f/4, f/5.6, f/8, f/11, f/16, f/22, and so on.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] For example, f/8 lets four times more light into the camera as f/16 does.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] A shutter speed of 1⁄50 s with an f/4 aperture gives the same exposure value as a 1⁄100 s shutter speed with an f/2.8 aperture, and also the same exposure value as a 1⁄200 s shutter speed with an f/2 aperture, or 1⁄25 s at f/5.6.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] In addition to its effect on exposure, the shutter speed changes the way movement appears in photographs.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Very short shutter speeds can be used to freeze fast-moving subjects, for example at sporting events.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Very long shutter speeds are used to intentionally blur a moving subject for effect.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Short exposure times are sometimes called "fast", and long exposure times "slow".
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Adjustments to the aperture need to be compensated by changes of the shutter speed to keep the same (right) exposure.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] In early days of photography, available shutter speeds were not standardized, though a typical sequence might have been 1⁄10 s, 1⁄25 s, 1⁄50 s, 1⁄100 s, 1⁄200 s and 1⁄500 s; neither were apertures or film sensitivity (at least 3 different national standards existed).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] With this scale, each increment roughly doubles the amount of light (longer time) or halves it (shorter time).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] The ability of the photographer to take images without noticeable blurring by camera movement is an important parameter in the choice of the slowest possible shutter speed for a handheld camera.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] The rough guide used by most 35 mm photographers is that the slowest shutter speed that can be used easily without much blur due to camera shake is the shutter speed numerically closest to the lens focal length.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] For example, for handheld use of a 35 mm camera with a 50 mm normal lens, the closest shutter speed is 1⁄60 s (closest to "50"), while for a 200 mm lens it is recommended not to choose shutter speeds below 1⁄200 s.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] This rule can be augmented with knowledge of the intended application for the photograph, an image intended for significant enlargement and closeup viewing would require faster shutter speeds to avoid obvious blur.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Through practice and special techniques such as bracing the camera, arms, or body to minimize camera movement, using a monopod or a tripod, slower shutter speeds can be used without blur.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] If a shutter speed is too slow for hand holding, a camera support, usually a tripod, must be used.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Image stabilization on digital cameras or lenses can often permit the use of shutter speeds 3–4 stops slower (exposures 8–16 times longer).
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Shutter priority refers to a shooting mode used in cameras.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] It allows the photographer to choose a shutter speed setting and allow the camera to decide the correct aperture.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] This is sometimes referred to as Shutter Speed Priority Auto Exposure, or TV (time value on Canon cameras) mode, S mode on Nikons and most other brands.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] The photograph to the right was taken with a slower shutter speed than that to the left, creating a more pronounced motion blur effect and longer streaks of light from vehicle headlamps.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Shutter speed is one of several methods used to control the amount of light recorded by the camera's digital sensor or film.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] It is also used to manipulate the visual effects of the final image.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Slower shutter speeds are often selected to suggest the movement of an object in a still photograph.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Excessively fast shutter speeds can cause a moving subject to appear unnaturally frozen.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] For instance, a running person may be caught with both feet in the air with all indication of movement lost in the frozen moment.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] When a slower shutter speed is selected, a longer time passes from the moment the shutter opens till the moment it closes.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] More time is available for movement in the subject to be recorded by the camera as a blur.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] When slower shutter-speeds, in excess of about half a second, are used on running water, the water in the photo will have a ghostly white appearance reminiscent of fog.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] This effect can be used in landscape photography.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Zoom burst is a technique which entails the variation of the focal length of a zoom lens during a longer exposure.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] In the moment that the shutter is opened, the lens is zoomed in, changing the focal length during the exposure.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] The center of the image remains sharp, while the details away from the center form a radial blur, which causes a strong visual effect, forcing the eye into the center of the image.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] The following list provides an overview of common photographic uses for standard shutter speeds.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Motion picture cameras used in traditional film cinematography employ a mechanical rotating shutter.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] The shutter rotation is synchronized with film being pulled through the gate, hence shutter speed is a function of the frame rate and shutter angle.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] With a traditional shutter angle of 180°, film is exposed for 1⁄48 second at 24 frame/s.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] To avoid effect of light interference when shooting under artificial lights or when shooting television screens and computer monitors, 1⁄50 s (172.8°) or 1⁄60 s (144°) shutter is often used.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Electronic video cameras do not have mechanical shutters and allow setting shutter speed directly in time units.
[src:motion-blur-rendering/shutter-speed] Professional video cameras often allow selecting shutter speed in terms of shutter angle instead of time units, especially those that are capable of overcranking or undercranking.
